## Describe the Permissions String

The file `project_t.txt` had the following permissions string:

-rw-rw-r--


This is a 10-character string that Linux uses to define access levels for different user categories and to identify the resource type:

| Characters | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `-` (1st) | Regular file |
| `rw-` (2nd–4th) | **Owner** — read and write |
| `rw-` (5th–7th) | **Group** — read and write |
| `r--` (8th–10th) | **Other** — read only |

---

## Change File Permissions

After examining the baseline permissions, I found files that granted **write access to other users**, violating the organization's security policy. Write permissions for users outside the intended group increase the risk of unauthorized or accidental file modification.

I used the `chmod` command to remove write access for other users:
bash
chmod o-w <filename>


This preserved proper access for the file owner and group while restricting others.

Additionally, I identified that `project_m.txt` granted **read access to the group**, even though it was intended to be restricted to the file owner only. I removed group read permissions:
bash
chmod g-r project_m.txt


![Figure 2: Updated permissions after removing write access for other users](images/fig2-chmod-other.png)

![Figure 3: Updated permissions for project_m.txt after removing group read access](images/fig3-chmod-group.png)

---

## Change File Permissions on a Hidden File

Hidden files are easily overlooked during routine audits, so they were also included in this review.

The hidden file `.project_x.txt` had been archived and should not have been modifiable by any user. I found it still had unnecessary **write permissions**.

I adjusted the permissions to read-only for both user and group:
bash
chmod u=r,g=r .project_x.txt


This ensured the integrity of the archived file by preventing any modifications.

![Figure 4: Updated permissions for .project_x.txt after removing write access](images/fig4-hidden-file.png)

---

## Change Directory Permissions

As a final step, I reviewed the `drafts` subdirectory. The group had **execute permissions**, which allowed them to access the directory and its contents. Since this directory contained draft and potentially sensitive information, this level of access was inappropriate.

I removed execute permissions for the group:
bash
chmod g-x drafts


This ensured that only the file owner could access and navigate the directory.

![Figure 5: Updated permissions for the drafts directory after removing group execute access](images/fig5-directory-perms.png)

